'''Kay WalkingStick''' (born 1935) is a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] painter and educator. She is enrolled in the [[Cherokee Nation]] and of [[Ho-Chunk]] descent.<ref name=les>Lester, 59607</ref> She currently resides in New York and was a Professor of Art at [[Cornell University]] from 1988-2005.

==Background==
Kay WalkingStick was born in [[Syracuse, New York]] in 1935. She earned her BFA from [[Beaver College]] in [[Glenside, Pennsylvania]] and her MFA from the [[Pratt Institute]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=les/>

==Artwork==
WalkingStick works with oils primarily, but also acrylic, watercolor, mixed media,<ref name=les/> encaustic, copper,<ref name=big>Lesk, 35</ref> charcoal, and gold leaf. She is known in particular for her mixed-media diptychs that juxtapose symbolic, abstract landscapes with representational landscapes. Of these she says, "No doubt the diptych form is interesting to me because I am bi-racial. Two sides singing in concert, each very different from the other yet united as a whole."<ref>Lippard, 185-6</ref>

